package sample.test;

import java.io.UnsupportedEncodingException;
import java.nio.charset.*;
import java.nio.*;


public class Utf8Util
{

    /**
	 * Takes a unicode string and returns the UTF-8 encoded byte array.
	 * 
	 * @param unicodeStr the string with the unicodes
	 * @return a UTF-8 encoded byte array
	 */
    public static byte[] toUtf8Bytes(String unicodeStr)throws CharacterCodingException, UnsupportedEncodingException
    {
    	byte[] retVal = null;

    	if (unicodeStr == null)
    	   return retVal;

    	Charset utf8Encoder = Charset.forName("UTF-8");  //$NON-NLS-1$
    	ByteBuffer buffer = utf8Encoder.encode(unicodeStr);
    	retVal = buffer.array();

    	return retVal;
    }

    /**
	 * Takes a unicode string and returns the UTF-8 encoded string.
	 * 
	 * To get the bytes of the returned UTF-8 encoded string, String.getBytes("UTF-8")
	 * must be used.
	 * 
	 * @param unicodeStr the string with the unicodes
	 * @return a UTF-8 string
	 */
    public static String toUtf8Str(String unicodeStr)throws CharacterCodingException, UnsupportedEncodingException
    {
    	String retVal = null;

    	if (unicodeStr == null)
    	   return retVal;

    	byte[] b = Utf8Util.toUtf8Bytes(unicodeStr);

    	// MUST contruct the stirng with the UTF-8 char set!
    	retVal = new String(b, "UTF-8");

    	return retVal;
    }
}

The package documentation for org.eclipse.core.commands includes the following example:
	CommandManager manager = new CommandManager();
	Category category = manager.getCategory("categoryId");
	...

This example will compile and run, but it does not do anything useful.  The CommandManager is, in practice, a singleton.  You can create and programatically manipulate a second instance, but it will have no effect, since the workbench will continue to use its original unmodified copy.  The documentation should read:
	ICommandService manager = (ICommandService)PlatformUI.getWorkbench().getAdapter(ICommandService.class);
	Category category = manager.getCategory("categoryId");
	...

This will get the master CommandManager and produce the desired effect.
The CommandManager constructor should probably also direct users to lookup the singleton rather than constructing a new instance.

