20060809

The Javadoc of ISourceReference.getSourceRange() specs:
 * @return the source range, or <code>null</code> if this element has no 
 *   associated source code

The implemenation in BinaryMember.getSourceRange() is:
	SourceMapper mapper= getSourceMapper();
	if (mapper != null) {
           ...
	} else {
		return SourceMapper.UNKNOWN_RANGE;
	}
and SourceMapper.UNKNOWN_RANGE is 'new SourceRange(-1, 0)'

Consider the code:
   class Base {
      virtual void virtualMethod();
   };
   class Derived : public Base {
      void virtualMethod();
   };

   void test() {
       Base* mybase= new Derived();
       mybase->virtualMethod();
   }

When you look at the call tree of Derived::polymorphicMethod() the Call Hierarchy does not reveal the call made by the function test(). Indeed the reference in the function is a reference to Base::polymorphicMethod(). Nevertheless the Call Hierarchy should show the reference.

What you demand is impossible, unless you can solve the Halting Problem for this program:

#include "your_example.h"

Base* foo(); //a library function

void main()
{
    while(!dynamic_cast<Derived*>(foo()));
}

In the code below the two references to 'virtualMethod()' are quite different.
In the second case the virtual mechanism is disabled. This information is relevant when computing Call Hierarchies and should be stored in the PDom.

Consider the code:
   class Base {
      void test();
      virtual void virtualMethod();
   };
   class Derived : public Base {
      void virtualMethod();
   };

   void Base::test() {
       virtualMethod();
       Base::virtualMethod();
   }
